{
  "answer": "**Allama Iqbal** opens his poem \"Himalaya\" from *Bang-E-Dara Part 1* (1924) by directly addressing the mountain with these lines:\n\n> Himalaya[^1]  \n> O Himalaya, rampart of the realm of Hindustan,[^2]  \n> The sky bows down to kiss your brow, as is its plan.[^2]\n\nThese verses personify the Himalaya as a protective barrier (\"rampart\") for Hindustan (India), emphasizing its majestic and eternal presence.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/25-himalaya/translation/#p-227c36/).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/25-himalaya/translation/#p-b8c905/).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 25 \"Himalaya\" ([full chapter](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/25-himalaya/translation/)).",
